snippet.textDisplay:
Just one more tip from a pro detailer!

Before you go to apply your paint sealant (wax/synthetic sealant/etc) after paint correction, you'll want you wipe down the paint with some sort of isopropyl alcohol-water mixture. More commonly referred to as "IPA mixes", these can be found pre-mixed in stores or you can mix some yourself. (Generally a 50-50 mix of IPA and water is a good starting point) This will help remove a lot of the residual oils from the polishing liquids that still may be left on the paint. This will give you better adhesion between the painted surface and your sealant, and can give you even just that extra 1% closer to a perfect finish!
snippet.textOriginal:

snippet.textDisplay:
In 1998 I bought a 1988 Nissan 240sx off a guy at work for $300. He hadn't washed it since the day he bought it and had just put about 60 plastic mats down to cover the carpets throughout the car. It had about 160,000 miles on it, but ran like a champ. I legitimately thought the car was that beige/tan color. Got it home and as I washed it, I figured out it might be white. Went through two jars of cleaner wax and yep, white. If that car you're detailing is a 4/10 bad, this Nissan was a 10/10. We got it down to a 2/10. He had put these ugly honeycomb gold wheels on it. Ripped them off and found some aftermarkets and a U-Pull-It that had decent tires.


Some idiot was curbstoning down the road and had a 1987 Porsche 944 Turbo on his front lawn that had been sitting there for three years. Flat tires, just looked ouch. Had been repainted competition yellow. He told me "the engine is done". I brought my buddy up who was a mechanic at a Porsche dealership here outside of Philly. He had me take the guy outback and told me to rev the loudest car I could find. I picked an IROC with a hole in the exhaust.


My buddy started telling me what a POS it was when I got back. That was the sign. I traded that 240sx with about $400 worth of parts to this guy for what he thought was a 944 Turbo that needed a new engine, tires, etc. My buddy bought me the water cooler for it with his discount for $312, we put it in that night, bought a set of tires and replaced two outside tie rods. 4 months later I hit a deer with that car and the insurance check for my totaled 944 was $31,000.


Flipped $700 into $31,000 my freshman year of college. Love people who can't fix their own cars and are idiots. Bought an Acura Integra Type R in 2000 with that money that I still freaking own 20 years later. Only has 57,000 miles on it.
